						               													<description>One in the series of &amp;quot;Max Haines Invites You To An Evening of Murder (tm)&amp;quot; party games. Plays like the &amp;quot;How to Host a Murder&amp;quot; series.  This particular edition is The Eternal Cruise. From the invitations...&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Crime Scene: Captain Scott Emery is missing at sea.  He disappeared late last evening while inspecting his ship, the Moonlight Princess, on a cruise from Vancouver to Alaska.  A search was organized.  His cap was discovered on the upper deck amid scattered chairs and signs of a struggle.  No other traces of the captain were found.  It is obvious he met with foul play.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The Suspects:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Tobie Corbett. A personal guest of the captain.  She's very quiet and prefers a good novel to the lively entertainment of the cruise.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Tanya Corbett.  Tobie's twin sister and traveling companion.  She is more outgoing and enjoys life to the fullest.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;J.D. Nast.  A wealthy oil tycoon.  A big and boisterous man who loves a good cigar and a good time.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Mary-Lou Nash.  A 'Southern Belle' vacationing with her husband.  She's always looking for new and exciting adventures.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Falcon Marlowe.  A little fellow on leave from the British Embassy.  Sailing isn't really is cup of tea... pity.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Tim Sawyer.  First Mate - an officer and a gentleman.  He's tall, handsome and always under control.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Rita Fendley.  As the ship's cruise director, she keeps the passengers in good humor with a busy itinerary.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Steve Walker.  A free-lance photographer on assignment.  An unfriendly type, strictly on board to work.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
